	&nbsp ˈenərˌvāt
	&nbsp <i>verb</i>
	&nbsp cause (someone) to feel drained of energy or vitality; weaken.
	&nbsp The champagne appeared to enervate her ability to focus on the competition.
]
(link-reveal: "bodhisattva")[
	&nbsp ˌbōdiˈsätvə,-ˈsət-
	&nbsp <i>noun</i>
	&nbsp (in Mahayana Buddhism) a person who is able to reach nirvana but delays doing so out of compassion in order to save suffering beings.
	&nbsp The bodhisattva always let him eat the last piece of pizza.
]
(link-reveal: "diaphanous")[
	&nbsp dīˈafənəs
	&nbsp <i>adjective</i>
	&nbsp (especially of fabric) light, delicate, and translucent.
	&nbsp You could see she was quite cold in that skin-tight, diaphanous gown.
]
(link-reveal: "impecunious")[
	&nbsp ˌimpəˈkyo͞onēəs
	&nbsp <i>adjective</i>
	&nbsp having little or no money.
	&nbsp The impecunious student accepted the high-interest rate loan.
